He is, indeed, probably entitled to all the credit that has been claimed for him, as throughout a just and liberal ruler of the provinces; the evi· dence for which is by no means confined to the early period of his principate. The temple founded in Asia in 776, A. n. 23², the similar request from Hispania Baetica in 778, A. n. 25³, appear genuine expres· sions of gratitude for punishment of official oppression⁴ ; and it is probably only because the latter application was refused, that more were not forthcoming ⁵. Medal⁶ and statue⁷ alike attest the feeling of Asia for his liberality after its ruinous earthquake3 inscriptions in the pro· vinces ⁸ and even in Rome ⁹ give him epithets by no means constantly applied to princes in such documents.

But, after all, the heart of the empire was still the senate of Rome in its relation to the prince: andis those who should have been the most valued instruments of his administration are seen shrinking terror-strichen from the public service, and absorbed in the effort to save themselves ς it is · impossible that the general effect could have been other than disastrous.

If our other evidence were more questionable than it is, the decline of literature would alone confirm it. Not but that even the Augustan age is nearly stripped of literary genius, as the great spirits born and trained ” under the Republic pass away; and the few survivors at the succession of Tiberius attest by their position the change of times. The great historiari of Rome had, as it seems, abruptly closed his work, and retired to his native Padua; the only great living poet was pining in exile on the Euxine. But from even the survival of such names it is indeed a descent, to a generation in which Velleius and Valerius Maximus, the sables of Phaedrus, and the rhetorical writings of M.
